<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate how many tiles I need?", answer: "Measure the total area to be tiled in square feet. Divide the area by the size of each tile (including grout line) to get the base count. Add 10% waste for straight layouts or 15-20% for diagonal or complex patterns. For example, a 100 sq ft floor with 12x12 inch tiles needs about 110 tiles with 10% waste." },
  { question: "How much grout do I need for my tile project?", answer: "Grout quantity depends on tile size, grout joint width, and tile thickness. Larger tiles with narrow grout lines need less grout, while small mosaic tiles with wide joints need significantly more. As a general guide, a 25-pound bag of sanded grout covers 100 to 200 square feet of 12x12 inch tiles with 1/8-inch joints." },
  { question: "What grout width should I use?", answer: "For rectified (precision-cut) tiles, use 1/16 to 1/8 inch grout lines. Standard ceramic and porcelain tiles typically use 1/8 to 3/16 inch joints. Natural stone tiles need 1/8 to 1/4 inch joints to accommodate size variation. Mosaic tiles on mesh sheets usually come with pre-set spacing of about 1/8 inch." },
  { question: "How much thin-set adhesive do I need?", answer: "One 50-pound bag of thin-set mortar covers approximately 60 to 80 square feet using a 1/4 x 1/4 inch square-notch trowel. Larger tiles require larger trowel notches and more thin-set per square foot. For large-format tiles over 15 inches, back-butter the tile in addition to spreading thin-set on the substrate for full coverage." },
  { question: "How much extra tile should I buy for waste?", answer: "Add 10% waste for a standard straight-lay floor installation. Add 15% for diagonal layouts, which produce more cuts. Add 20% for complex patterns, small rooms with many cuts, or natural stone that may have defects. Always keep a few extra tiles for future repairs, as tile colors and textures can vary between production batches." }
]) %>

