    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Tile Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Accurate tile estimates prevent both shortages and excess spending. Enter the total area to be tiled in square feet. Specify the tile length and width in inches, along with the grout joint width. The calculator accounts for the grout spacing when computing the effective area each tile covers. Set a waste percentage to account for cuts, breakage, and pattern matching. The result tells you exactly how many tiles to buy, plus the estimated grout and thin-set adhesive quantities.
      </p>
      <p>
        The grout estimate is based on the total linear feet of grout joints multiplied by the cross-sectional area of each joint. The adhesive estimate assumes a standard 50-pound bag of thin-set mortar covering approximately 60 square feet with a quarter-inch square-notch trowel. Larger tiles or uneven substrates may require more adhesive.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Choosing the Right Tile</h2>
      <p>
        Ceramic tiles are the most affordable option and work well for walls and light-traffic floors. Porcelain tiles are denser, more water-resistant, and suitable for high-traffic areas, outdoor installations, and wet environments. Natural stone tiles like marble, travertine, and slate offer unique beauty but require sealing and more careful maintenance. Large-format tiles create a sleek, modern look with fewer grout lines but require a perfectly flat substrate and careful installation technique.
      </p>

      <h3>Substrate Preparation</h3>
      <p>
        The substrate must be clean, dry, flat, and structurally sound before tiling. Cement backer board is the preferred substrate for wet areas like showers and tub surrounds. For floors, the maximum allowable variation is 1/8 inch over 10 feet. Use a self-leveling compound to correct uneven concrete or plywood subfloors. Never install tile directly over particleboard, oriented strand board, or vinyl flooring without proper underlayment.
      </p>

      <h3>Layout and Cutting Tips</h3>
      <p>
        Always dry-lay tiles before applying adhesive to check the pattern and identify the best starting point. Begin from the center of the room and work outward to ensure symmetrical cuts at the walls. Avoid narrow sliver cuts less than half a tile width at the edges, as they look unprofessional and are difficult to install. A wet tile saw produces the cleanest cuts for porcelain and natural stone, while a manual tile cutter works well for straight cuts on standard ceramic tiles.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How do I calculate how many tiles I need?</h3>
      <p>
        Measure the total area in square feet. Divide by the size of each tile including the grout line to get the base count. Add 10 percent waste for straight layouts or 15 to 20 percent for diagonal or complex patterns.
      </p>

      <h3>How much grout do I need for my tile project?</h3>
      <p>
        Grout quantity depends on tile size, joint width, and tile thickness. A 25-pound bag of sanded grout covers 100 to 200 square feet of 12x12 inch tiles with 1/8-inch joints. Smaller tiles with wider joints require significantly more grout.
      </p>

      <h3>What grout width should I use?</h3>
      <p>
        Rectified tiles use 1/16 to 1/8 inch joints. Standard ceramic and porcelain tiles use 1/8 to 3/16 inch joints. Natural stone tiles need 1/8 to 1/4 inch joints to accommodate size variation.
      </p>

      <h3>How much thin-set adhesive do I need?</h3>
      <p>
        One 50-pound bag covers approximately 60 to 80 square feet with a 1/4 x 1/4 inch trowel. Larger tiles require larger trowel notches and more thin-set per square foot. Back-butter tiles over 15 inches for full coverage.
      </p>

      <h3>How much extra tile should I buy for waste?</h3>
      <p>
        Add 10 percent for standard straight layouts, 15 percent for diagonal, and 20 percent for complex patterns or small rooms with many cuts. Always keep spare tiles for future repairs.
      </p>

